d were probably domesticated for their potential in making quantities of alcoholic beverages. These include the delectable rice wines of China and Japan, the corn beers of the Americas, and the millet and sorghum drinks of Africa. Humans also learned how to make mead from honey and wine from exotic fruits of all kinds-even from the sweet pulp of the cacao (chocolate) fruit in the New World. The perfect drink, it turns out-whether it be mind-altering, medicinal, a religious symbol, a social lubricant, or artistic inspiration-has not only been a profound force in history, but may be fundamental to the human condition itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAlcoholic beveragesxHistory. 0aAlcoholic beveragesxSocial aspects. 0aDrinking of alcoholic beveragesxHistory. 0aDrinking of alcoholic beveragesxSocial aspects. 4aagrarian society. 4aalcohol history. 4aalcoholic beverages. 4aanthropology. 4aarchaeology. 4acacao. 4acoffee table book. 4acorn beer. 4acreation of alcohol. 4aevolution. 4afermented beverages. 4afermenting. 4afood and sociology. 4afood and wine. 4afood history. 4agastronomy. 4ahistory of alcohol. 4ahuman condition. 4aliquid courage. 4amead. 4amillet. 4amodern world. 4aprovocative hypothesis. 4areligious symbol. 4arice wine. 4arole of alcohol in society. 4asearch for booze. 4asocial lubricant. 4asorghum. 4aspirits. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520944688423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/97805209446